    "direction": null,
    "comprehension": null,
    "content": "What happens to the guard cells when water flows into them?",
    "options": [
      {
        "identifier": "1",
        "content": "The guard cells close."
      },
      {
        "identifier": "2",
        "content": "Stomatal pores open."
      },
      {
        "identifier": "3",
        "content": "Stomatal pores shrink."
      },
      {
        "identifier": "4",
        "content": "Stomatal pores close."
      }
    ],
    "correct_options": [
      "2"
    ],
    "explanation": "<p>When water flows into the guard cells, the stomatal pores open.</p>\n<p>Guard cells are specialized cells located on the leaf epidermis that control the opening and closing of stomata (pores). Here’s the detailed process:</p>\n\n<p><p><strong>Turgor Pressure Increase</strong>: When water enters the guard cells, they become turgid (swollen) due to the increased turgor pressure.</p></p>\n<p><p><strong>Guard Cell Shape Change</strong>: The guard cells, which have a unique kidney or bean shape, change shape as they become turgid. This change in shape causes the stomatal pore between them to open.</p></p>\n<p><p><strong>Gas Exchange Facilitation</strong>: The opening of stomatal pores facilitates the exchange of gases, allowing carbon dioxide to enter for photosynthesis and oxygen and water vapor to leave.</p></p>\n\n<p>Thus, when water flows into them, the guard cells become turgid and cause the stomatal pores to open.</p>\n<p>Option 2: <strong>Stomatal pores open</strong> is correct.</p>",
